<div id="review_3477097792" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3477097792" />
    <a title="Joel Wentz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16113948-joel-wentz"><img alt="Joel Wentz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1358382526p2/16113948.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3477097792?book_show_action=true">Aug 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joel Wentz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joel Wentz" href="/user/show/16113948-joel-wentz">Joel Wentz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/22011271-letters-and-papers-from-prison">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3477097792" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6540945364228986149">This is a stunning, beautiful and of course, tragic collection of short writings from the brilliant Bonhoeffer. As with any collection like this, the reader should know that it obviously wasn&apos;t originally written/intended for publication, so do not expect the systematically-organized theological thinking that shows up in books like &quot;Discipleship.&quot; Instead, you get a deeply personal glimpse into the emotions and raw philosophical-theological pondering of Bonhoeffer near the end of his life.<br/><br/>My exp</span>
  <span id="freeText6540945364228986149" style="display:none">This is a stunning, beautiful and of course, tragic collection of short writings from the brilliant Bonhoeffer. As with any collection like this, the reader should know that it obviously wasn't originally written/intended for publication, so do not expect the systematically-organized theological thinking that shows up in books like "Discipleship." Instead, you get a deeply personal glimpse into the emotions and raw philosophical-theological pondering of Bonhoeffer near the end of his life.<br /><br />My experience of reading this was actually fairly emotional, as letters will contain painful glimpses into his personal life - the friends and family he missed so dearly, his internal wrestling match with choices he made throughout his career - and then suddenly on comes across a lightning bolt of theological reflection. Of course, the famous section on "religionless Christianity" is included here - which is indeed exquisite - but there are long sections on the state of religion in the world, the place of Christianity within the development of man, and brilliant reflections on how the church should carry Christian thinking forward. It's incredible stuff, and makes it oh-so-much more tragic that the we lost this man when we did.<br /><br />I absolutely think this should be read alongside Bonhoeffer's earlier works, as it not only provides a personal glimpse into his psyche, but also stretches, deepens and clarifies his legacy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6540945364228986149" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

