<div id="review_2926102672" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2926102672" />
    <a title="Harry Allagree" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8488865-harry-allagree"><img alt="Harry Allagree" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582069740p2/8488865.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2926102672?book_show_action=true">Aug 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Harry Allagree" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Harry Allagree" href="/user/show/8488865-harry-allagree">Harry Allagree</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781506402741" href="/book/show/27625857-letters-and-papers-from-prison">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2926102672" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9316438452548266569">A book of over 500 pages is always a challenge, but this Fortress Press volume translation from the German Works of Dietrich Bonhoeffer reads well. It&apos;s divided into 4 Parts: the interrogation period; awaiting the trial; holding out for the coup attempt (on Hitler&apos;s life); and after the failure. These are sandwiched in between a prologue, which is insightful in terms of what Bonhoeffer analyzes that he&apos;s up against, and an epilogue in which one of the Bonhoeffer family survivors, Dietrich&apos;s brot</span>
  <span id="freeText9316438452548266569" style="display:none">A book of over 500 pages is always a challenge, but this Fortress Press volume translation from the German Works of Dietrich Bonhoeffer reads well. It's divided into 4 Parts: the interrogation period; awaiting the trial; holding out for the coup attempt (on Hitler's life); and after the failure. These are sandwiched in between a prologue, which is insightful in terms of what Bonhoeffer analyzes that he's up against, and an epilogue in which one of the Bonhoeffer family survivors, Dietrich's brother, Karl-Friedrich, looks back on the fast moving developments between February &amp; April 9 of 1945, culminating in Bonhoeffer's execution. Charles Marsh's book, Strange Glory, and other biographies of Bonhoeffer piece together the probable timeline &amp; details of his execution.<br /><br />This collection of letters &amp; papers, mostly to his family members, provides a peek into the soul of a rather complex man/friend/fiancé/pastor/theologian. As the book progresses one becomes aware of the various new insights, humanistically &amp; theologically, which Bonhoeffer acquires. By the last section, the letters reflect his realization that he will never be set free, intuitions of which are mentioned throughout the book. I believe that any serious reader of Bonhoeffer's works can't help but come away with a multitude of questions and much to think about. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9316438452548266569" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


