    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_791196920" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/791196920" />
    <a title="Kpent" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4354401-kpent"><img alt="Kpent" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/791196920?book_show_action=true">Dec 15, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kpent" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kpent" href="/user/show/4354401-kpent">Kpent</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer791196920" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer379457144247052683">&quot;Dietrich Bonhoeffer: Letters &amp; Papers from Prison&quot; is an interesting look at prison life, WW2, Bonhoeffer&apos;s family relationships, friendship (which is most of the latter part of the book, along with practical Christianity) and theology. It&apos;s haunting to read letters where the writer and reader are ignorant, but you can count the months down to when one will die. <br/><br/>I thought this was beautiful. In the middle of Dietrich&apos;s last letter to his friend Eberhard, he wrote: &quot;Please don&apos;t ever get anxious</span>
  <span id="freeText379457144247052683" style="display:none">"Dietrich Bonhoeffer: Letters &amp; Papers from Prison" is an interesting look at prison life, WW2, Bonhoeffer's family relationships, friendship (which is most of the latter part of the book, along with practical Christianity) and theology. It's haunting to read letters where the writer and reader are ignorant, but you can count the months down to when one will die. <br /><br />I thought this was beautiful. In the middle of Dietrich's last letter to his friend Eberhard, he wrote: "Please don't ever get anxious or worried about me, but don't forget to pray for me – I'm sure you don't! I am so sure of God's guiding hand that I hope I shall always be kept in that certainty. You must never doubt that I'm travelling with gratitude and cheerfulness along the road where I'm being led. My past life is brim-full of God's goodness, and my sins are covered by the forgiving love of Christ crucified. I'm most thankful for the people I have met, and I only hope that they never have to grieve about me, but that they, too, will always be certain of, and thankful for, God's mercy and forgiveness. Forgive my writing this. Don't let it grieve or upset you for a moment, but let it make you happy. But I did want to say it once, and I couldn't think of anyone else who I could be sure would take it aright." <br /><br />He ends that letter: Now with all my heart I wish you further peace and quiet, outwardly and inwardly. God protect you and all of us and grant us a speedy reunion. With gratitude and loyalty and daily prayers. I'm always thinking of you. Your D."<br /><br />Isn't it interesting how the only earthly relationship that transcends this life is friendship? Family blood lines will cease; teacher/student, employer/employee, master/slave, etc. will all be gone as we know it (Matthew 22:29-30; Galatians 3), but friendship is a relationship built on heart and not on body or circumstances. I'm sure Eberhard Berthge, Bonhoeffer's friend, would have agreed it wasn't over even with death between.</span>
  <a data-text-id="379457144247052683" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


